  "prompt": "Which book will good for special theory of relativity for JAM PH?",
  "response": "For the Joint Admission Test for M.Sc. (JAM) in Physics, the **Special Theory of Relativity** is an important topic. Below are some recommended books that are suitable for JAM Physics preparation:\n\n### 1. **\"Introduction to Special Relativity\" by Robert Resnick**\n   - One of the most popular books for beginners.\n   - Provides a clear and concise introduction to the concepts of special relativity.\n   - Includes solved examples and exercises to help understand the topic.\n\n### 2. **\"Special Relativity\" by A.P. French**\n   - A well-written book with a good balance of theory and applications.\n   - Suitable for undergraduate students and includes detailed explanations of key concepts.\n   - Useful for JAM Physics preparation.\n\n### 3. **\"Classical Electrodynamics\" by J.D. Jackson**\n   - Includes a section on special relativity that is advanced but thorough.\n   - Recommended for students who want a deeper understanding of relativity in the context of electrodynamics.\n\n### 4. **\"The Special Theory of Relativity\" by David Bohm**\n   - A concise and insightful book that focuses on the conceptual aspects of relativity.\n   - Suitable for students who want to build a strong foundation in the subject.\n\n### 5. **\"Relativity: The Special and General Theory\" by Albert Einstein**\n   - A classic book written by Einstein himself.\n   - Provides an intuitive understanding of the theory from the creator's perspective.\n\n### Additional Resources:\n- **NPTEL lectures** on Special Relativity (available online) can be very helpful.\n- **Previous years' JAM question papers** to practice problems related to special relativity.\n\nFor JAM Physics, focus on understanding the basics, solving numerical problems, and practicing derivations. Resnick's or French's book would be a great starting point.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
